# Market Equilibrium

Assumptions

  1. Market economy
  2. Partial equilibrium model
    • Consumers’ utility functions take a quasilinear form with respect to a numeraire.

Definition (Market Economy / Private Ownership Economy). Individual consumers have ownership rights to various assets and are free to trade these assests in the marketplace for other assests or goods. Firms decide on their production plan and trade in the market to secure necessary inputs and sells the resulting outputs.

  • Definition (Competitive Market Economy). The market economy in which every relevant good is traded in a market at publicly known prices and all agents act as price takers.

Definition (Market Equilibrium). A market equilibrium is an outcome of a market economy in which each agent in the economy is doing as well as he can given the acitons of all other agents.

# Competitive Markets

Assumptions

  1. I consumers (indexed by i=1,…,I)
  2. J firms (indexed by j=1,…,J)
    • Each firm j's production possibilities are summarized by the production set Yj⊂RL.
  3. L goods (indexed by ℓ=1,…,L)
    • The total amount of each good initially available in the economy, called the total endowment of good ℓ, is denoted by ωℓ≥0 for ℓ=1,…,L.
  4. Consumer i initially owns ωℓi of good ℓ, where ∑iωℓi=ωℓ.
    • Denote consumer i's vector of endowments by ωi=(ω1i,…,ωLi).
  5. Consumer i owns a share θij of firm j (where ∑iθij=1), giving him a claim to fraction θij of firm j's profits.

Definition (Economic Allocation). An economic allocation (x1,…,xI,y1,…,yJ) is a specification of a consumption vector xi∈Xi, for each consumer i=1,…,I and a production vector yj∈Yj for each firm j=1,…,J. The allocation (x1,…,xI,y1,…,yJ) is feasible if

∑i=1Ixℓi≤ωℓ+∑j=1Jyℓjfor ℓ=1,…,L.

Definition (Pareto Optimal/ Pareto Efficiency). A feasible allocation (x1,…,xI,y1,…,yJ) is Pareto optimal if there is no other feasible allocation (x1′,…,xI′,y1′,…,yJ′) such that ui(xi′)≥ui(xi) for all i=1,…,I and ui(xi′)>ui(xi) for some i.

The concept of Pareto optimality offers a minimal and uncontroversial test that any social optimal economic outcome should pass. (No waste.)

# Competitive Equilibria

Definition (Competitive Equilibrium). The allocation (x1∗,…,xI∗,y1∗,…,yJ∗) and price vector p∗∈RL constitute a competitive equilibrium if the following conditions are satisfied:

  1. Profit maximization: For each firm j, yj∗ solvesmaxyj∈Yjp∗⋅yj.
  2. Utility maximization: For each consumer i, xi∗ solvesmaxxi∈Xiui(xi)s.t.p∗⋅xi≤p∗⋅ωi+∑j=1Jθij(p∗⋅yj∗).
  3. Market clearing: For each good ℓ=1,…,L,∑i=1Ixℓi∗=ωℓ+∑j=1Jyℓj∗.

Lemma (Markets Clear). If the allocation (x1,…,xI,y1,…,yJ) and price vector p≫0 satisfy the market clearing condition above for all goods ℓ≠k, and if every consumer’s budget constraint is satisfied with equality, so that p⋅xi=p⋅ωi+∑jθijp⋅yj for all i, then the market for good k also clears.

# Partial Equilibrium

# Consumers' Problem

Assumptions

  1. Let m represents other goods, and let each consumer's consumption set be R×R+. We can write the utility form as

    ui(mi,xi)=mi+ϕ(xi).

  2. We assume that ϕi(⋅) is bounded above and twice differentiable, with ϕi′(xi)>0 and ϕ″(xi)<0 at all xi>0.

  3. Assume that there is no initial endowment of good ℓ, so that all amounts consumed must be produced by the firms.

We normalize ϕi(0)=0, and also normalize the price of the numeraire to equal 1, and we let p denote the price of good ℓ.

Wealth effects for non-numeraire commodities are null.

Consumer i’s initial endowment of the numeraire is the scalar ωmi>0, and we let ωm=∑iωmi.

Consumer's maximization is

maxmi∈R,xi∈R+mi+ϕi(xi)s.t.mi+p∗xi≤ωmi+∑j=1Jθij(p∗qj∗−cj(qj∗))maxxi≥0ϕi(xi)−p∗xi+[ωmi+∑j=1Jθij(p∗qj∗−cj(qj∗))]⇒ϕi′(xi∗)≤p∗, with equality if xi∗>0

# Firms' Problem

Firm j's production set is

Yj={(−zj,qj):qj≥0andzj≥cj(qj)}
  • We assume that cj(⋅) is twice differentiable, with cj′(qj)>0 and cj″(qj)≥0 at all qj≥0.

Firm's maximization

maxqj≥0p∗qj−cj(qj)⇒p∗≤cj′(qj∗), with equality if qj∗>0

# Conclusion

Assumption

Assume that Maxiϕi′(0)>Minjcj′(0).

We can view the competitive equilibrium as involving an aggregate output level at which the marginal social benefit of good ℓ is exactly equal to its marginal cost.

# Comparative Statics

Assumptions

  1. Imagine that each consumer’s preferences are affected by a vector of exogenous parameters α∈RM so that the utility function ϕi(⋅) can be written as ϕi(xi,α).
  2. Each firm’s technology may be affected by a vector of exogenous parameters β∈RS, so that the cost function cj(⋅) can be written as cj(qj,β).
  3. Consumers and firms face taxes or subsidies that may make the effective (i.e., net of taxes and subsidies) price paid or received differ from the market price p. We let p^i(p,t) and p^j(p,t) denote, respectively, the effective price paid by consumer i and the effective price received by firm j given tax and subsidy parameters t∈RK.
    1. For example, if consumer i must pay a tax of ti (in units of the numeraire) per unit of good i purchased, then p^i(p,t)=p+ti.
    2. If consumer i instead faces a tax that is a percentage ti of the sales price, then p^i(p,t)=p(1+ti).

For given values (α,β,t):

ϕi′(xi∗,α)=p^i(p∗,t)i=1,…,I.cj′(qj∗,β)=p^j(p∗,t)j=1,…,J.∑i=1Ixi∗=∑j=1Jqj∗.

# Welfare Theorems in a Partial Equilibrium Context

When consumer preferences are quasilinear, the boundary of the economy's utility possibility set is linear and all points in this boundary are associated with consumption allocations that differ only in the distribution of the numeraire among consumers.

Thus, every Pareto optimal allocation must involve the quantities (x1∗,…,xI∗,q1∗,…,qJ∗) that extend this boundary as far out as possible.

  • We call these quantities the optimal consumption and production levels for good ℓ.
  • As long as these optimal consumption and production levels for good ℓ are uniquely determined, Pareto optimal allocations can differ only in the distribution of the numeraire among consumers.

The optimal consumption and production levels of good ℓ can be obtained as the solution to

max(x1,…,xI)≥0(q1,…,qJ)≥0∑i=1Iϕi(xi)−∑j=1Jcj(qj)+ωms.t.∑i=1Ixi−∑j=1Jqj=0

Definition (Marshallian Aggregate Surplus). The value of the term ∑iϕi(xi)−∑jcj(qj) is known as the Marshallian aggregate surplus.

# Fundamental Welfare Theorem

Proposition (The First Fundamental Welfare Theorem). If every relevant good is traded in a market at publicly known prices, and if households and firms act perfectly competitively, then the the price p∗ and allocation (x1∗,…,xI∗,q1∗,…,qJ∗) is Pareto optimal. That is, when markets are complete, any competitive equilibrium is necessary Pareto optimal.

Proposition (The Second Fundamental Welfare Theorem). If household preferences and firm production sets are convex,there is a complete set of markets with publicly known prices, and every agent acts as a price taker, then for any Pareto optimal levels of utility (u1∗,…,uI∗), there are transfers of the numeraire commodity (T1,…,TI) satisfying ∑iTi=0, such that a competitive equilibrium reached from the endowments (ωm1+T1,…,ωmI+TI) yields precisely the utilities (u1∗,…,uI∗).

The competitive price is exactly equal to the shadow price on the resource constraint for good ℓ in the Pareto optimality problem. In this sense, we can say that a good’s price in a competitive equilibrium reflects precisely its marginal social value.

# Welfare Analysis in the Partial Equilibrium Model

Assumptions

  1. Assume that the welfare judgments of society are embodied in a social welfare function W(u1,…,uI) assigning a social welfare value to every utility vector (u1,…,uI).
  2. Suppose that there is some central authority who redistributes wealth by means of transfers of the numeraire commodity in order to maximize social welfare.

If the authority always chooses the best policy, the critical simplification offered by the quasilinear specification of individual utility functions is that when there is a central authority who redistributes wealth in this manner, changes in social welfare can be measured by changes in the Marshallian aggregate surplus for any social welfare function that society may have.

A change in the consumption and production levels of good ℓ leads to an increase in welfare if and only if it increases the Marshallian aggregate surplus

S(x1,…,xI,q1,…,qJ)=∑i=1Iϕi(xi)−∑j=1Jcj(qj).

Assumptions

  1. Denoting by x=∑ixi the aggregate consumption of good ℓ, we assume that for any x, the individual consumptions of good ℓ are distributed optimally across consumers.
    • This condition will be satisfied if consumers act as price-takers and all consumers face the same price.
  2. Denoting by q=∑jqj the aggregate ouptput of good ℓ, we assume that the production of any total amount q is distributed optimally across frims.
    • We don't require that the price faced by consumers and firms be the same.

Consider now a differential change (dx1,…,dxI,dq1,…,dqJ) in the quantities of good ℓ consumed and produced satisfying ∑idxi=∑jdqj, and denote dx=∑idxi. The change in aggregate Marshallian surplus is then

dS=∑i=1Iϕi′(xi)dxi−∑j=1Jcj′(qj)dqj.

Since ϕi′(xi)=P(x) for all i, and cj′(qj)=C′(q) for all j, we get

dS=P(x)∑i=1Idxi−C′(q)∑j=1Jdqj.

Finally, since x=q and ∑jdqj=∑idxi=dx, this becomes

dS=[P(x)−C′(x)]dx.

We can integrate the equation above to express the total value of the aggregate Marshallian surplus at the aggregate consumption level x, denoted S(x), in terms of an integral of the difference between the inverse demand function and the industry marginal cost function,

S(x)=S0+∫0x[P(s)−C′(s)]ds,

where S0 is a constant of integration equal to the value of the aggregate surplus when there is no consumption or production of good ℓ.

# Free-Entry and Long-Run Competitive Equilibria

Assumptions

  1. Suppose that each of an infinite number of potential firms has access to a technology for producing good ℓ with cost function c(q), where q is the individual firm’s output of good ℓ.

    • c(0)=0.

  2. All active firms produce the same output level.

  3. Free Entry: A firm will enter the market if it can earn positive profits at the going market price and will exit if it can make only negative profits at any positive production level given this price.

Definition (Long-Run Competitive Equilibrium). Given an aggregate demand function x(p) and a cost function c(q) for each potentially active firm having c(0)=0, a triple (p∗,q∗,J∗) is a long-run competitive equilibrium if

  1. q∗ solves maxq≥0p∗q−c(q)
  2. x(p∗)=J∗q∗
  3. p∗q∗−c(q∗)=0

Long-run aggregate supply correspondence

Q(p)={∞ if π(p)>0{Q≥0:Q=Jq for some integer J≥0 and q∈q(p)} if π(p)=00 if π(p)<0

If the cost function c(⋅) exhibits constant returns to scale, J∗ and g∗ are indeterminate.

If c(⋅) is increasing and strictly convex, no long-run competitive equilibrium can exist.

Suppose, in particular, that c(⋅) has a unique efficient scale q―>0, and let the minimized level of average cost be c―=c(q―)/q―. Assume, moreover, that x(c)>0.

  • Equilibrium uniquely exists.
  • If the demand at price c―,x(c―), to be an integer multiple of q. Were this not so, no long-run equilibrium would exist.
